        'pageid' => 47722916,
        'title' => 'Prionyx',
        'feed' => 'Prionyx is a genus of wasps in the family Sphecidae. They are known to hunt and feed on grasshoppers.\n\n\n== Behavior ==\nPrior to laying their eggs the female Prionyx stings a grasshopper causing paralysis. She will then bury the grasshopper in a burrow she has excavated, lay an egg on the body, and then seal the burrow. When the egg develops it feeds on the grasshopper until it has matured, and then pupates.\n\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe name Prionyx comes from the Greek words \"Prion\" (Saw) and \"Onyx/Onychus\" (Claw), which refers to the saw-like endings on the creature\'s legs.\n\n\n== Species ==\nThese species belong to the genus Prionyx:\n\nData sources: i = ITIS, c = Catalogue of Life, g = GBIF, b = Bugguide.net WPC = Wojciech J. Pulawski\'s Catalog (Accessed March, 2025, but not in ITIS etc using same older source from 2019)\n\nNote: As a proposed replacement name for preoccupied Sphex chilensis Spinola, 1851, as used later by various authors, but in several sources as e.g. Prionyx chilensis (Spinola, 1851), e.g. after Amarante, 2002)\n\n\n== References ==',
